        <h3>Case 1: Heart Attack – Man VS Women</h3>

        <p>
        Recent studies and research show that man and women experience heart attacks quite differently.  The symptoms vary but women tend to show symptoms, which are not directly related to chest pains. Some of these symptoms include:
       <ul>
        <li>Neck, jaw, shoulder, upper back or abdominal discomfort</li>
        <li>Shortness of breath</li>
        <li>Right arm pain</li>
        <li>Nausea or vomiting</li>
        <li>Sweating</li>
        <li>Lightheadedness or dizziness</li>
        <li>Unusual fatigue</li>
    </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
        Men on the other hand show the better-known symptoms such as chest pain, chest pressure, and discomfort.  Traditionally diagnosis has been done using the golden standard, which is based on the symptoms man show.
        The Center for Gender Medicine aims to promote the differences and raise awareness among researchers, students, and the general public. In an ideal world all research, clinical trials, investigations in the medical world would be carried out with the distinct differentiation between male and female cells, specimens, and interactions. The Center would like to promote this ideal world.
        Watch the following TED Talk by Dr. Paula Johnson on how women and man experience heart diseases differently.

        </p>
