        <h3>Case 2: Stress Urinary Incontinence</h3>

        <p>In past years research has shown that there is a significant difference in ways man and women deal with stress urinary incontinence.  Some facts include:
       <ul>
        <li>More than 50% of man who undergo prostate surgery experience leakage due to SUI.</li>
        <li>Embarrassment and reluctance to seek medical advice is the key reason why many SUI get undetected in man.</li>
        <li>Man suffers from SUI usually after a surgery where else women suffer from various daily activities like coughing, laughing, or sneezing.</li>
        <li>Women are more likely to go under a surgery to treat SUI than man.</li>
        <li>In both groups the number of SUI are increasing.</li>
    </ul>
            </p>

        <p>
        SUI is often regarded as one of the least informed or talked about medical condition. Due to the embarrassing stigma associated with SUI and other conditions, both man and women feel uncomfortable to report or seek medical advice.
